SIMPLE: opeidoscope
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Opeidoscope
<hw>O*pei"do*scope</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/, <?/,
voice + <grk>e'i^dos</grk> form + <ets>-scope</ets>.]</ety>
<fld>(Physics)</fld> <def>An instrument, consisting of a tube having one
end open and the other end covered with a thin flexible membrane to the
center of which is attached a small mirror. It is used for exhibiting
upon a screen, by means of rays reflected from the mirror, the vibratory
motions caused by sounds produced at the open end of the tube, as by
speaking or singing into it.</def> <rj><au>A. E. Dolbear.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Opelet</ent>⟦br⟧
